Charles Fort was a 19th century anomaly researcher and writer, who believed a "sinister" civilization inhabited the Southern Pole and ridiculed science

He seems to be the first person to research the UFO phenomenon and to suspect it of alien origins, coined the term "teleportation", wrote about big cats in America, "out of place artefacts".

Overall Fort was the man to define what "paranormal" is and  to properly define it.

He seems to not have sincerely believed all of his writings, but just noted different curiosities and anomalies.

He talks of incidents of people seeing groups of men in the sky, theorized about continents existing ABOVE the sky, wrote about Earth not being shaped like a sphere.

Fort was also interested in cryptozoology, human abduction, werewolves, that early prehistorical humans had developed psychic abilities to survive as a species. He also mocked and distrusted Einstein's theories (together with most of science). en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Categoâ€¦

Honestly this man talked about literally every paranormal and conspiratorial theory that we today have, we are all his spiritual children, and he seems to be completely forgotten nowadays. I suggest everyone interested in unusual topics to look him up and read a bit more.

There is more to earthquakes than we think... have you heard of "earthquake weather"? The Greeks knew of it, but now some geologists start to suspect it's true, earthquakes are preceded by long periods of drought and high temperatures. How does this happen?

There are earthquake clouds, specific types of clouds appear in the days before a seismic event. Even more bizarre, have you heard of "earthquake lights"? In the night before an earthquake, mysterious lights appear in the horizon, near the area that will be struck.
